In your template, you use the `context_object_name` you defined in the view to loop through your data.

**Create templates/book_list.html:**

```html
{% extends 'base.html' %}

{% block content %}
<h1>Available Books</h1>
<ul>
    {% for book in all_books %}
        <li>{{ book.title }} - {{ book.date_published }}</li>
    {% empty %}
        <li>No books available yet.</li>
    {% endfor %}
</ul>
{% endblock %}
```

Django automatically generates a form object for you. You just need to place it inside an HTML `<form>` tag in your template.

**Create templates/book_form.html:**

```html
{% extends 'base.html' %}

{% block content %}
<h1>Add a New Book</h1>
<form method="POST">
    {% csrf_token %}
    {{ form.as_p }}  
    <button type="submit">Save Book</button>
</form>
<br>
<a href="{% url 'book-list' %}">Cancel</a>
{% endblock %}
```

To make the application functional, add an "Edit" button next to each book in your list or on the detail page.

**Update templates/book_list.html:**

```html
{% for book in all_books %}
    <li>
        {{ book.title }} 
        <a href="{% url 'book-update' book.pk %}">[Edit]</a>
    </li>
{% endfor %}
```

Instead of a simple list, the video demonstrates how to display your database records in a structured HTML table. This makes it easier to view multiple fields (like price, rating, and author) side-by-side.

**The Workflow:** You use a `{% for %}` loop to create a new `<tr>` (table row) for every book in your database.

**Handling Relationships:** For Many-to-Many fields (like Authors), you must run a nested loop inside the table cell:

```html
<td>
  {% for author in book.authors.all %}
    {{ author.first_name }} {{ author.last_name }}{% if not forloop.last %}, {% endif %}
  {% endfor %}
</td>
```
